{"id":"2209.05660","submitter":"Lucia Stein-Montalvo","authors":"Lucia Stein-Montalvo, Arman Guerra, Kanani Almeida, Ousmane Kodio, and\n  Douglas P. Holmes","title":"Wrinkling and developable cones in confined annular sheets","comments":"6 pages, 4 figures. Supplemental Information: 3 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Thin sheets respond to confinement by smoothly wrinkling, or by focusing\nstress into small, sharp regions. From engineering to biology, geology,\ntextiles, and art, these motifs have provoked decades of study. Yet, a\nframework to explain the morphological paths of confined, thin sheets awaits an\nunderstanding of how a wide range of intermediate confinement conditions drive\nspontaneous stress focusing. We probe this regime with experiments and\nmolecular dynamics (MD) simulations, in which circular sheets are flattened in\ntheir central region and quasi-statically drawn through a ring. Wrinkles\ndevelop in the outer, free region, then are replaced by a truncated cone, which\nforms in an abrupt transition to stress focusing. An analogy to pressure\nbuckling of an encased ring captures the force associated with this event.\nAdditional cones sequentially pattern the sheet, until axisymmetry is recovered\nin most geometries. Cone size is sensitive to geometry, which we explain with a\n1D model wherein concentrated strain acts as an effective elastic foundation.\nThis work contributes to the characterization of general confinement of thin\nsheets, while broadening the understanding of the d-cone, a fundamental element\nof stress focusing, as it appears in realistic settings.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Sep 2022 00:28:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-09-14"}
